Introduction and Data Loading

This study will compare the results of several algorithms on two (2) datasets: bigMovieLense and Groceries. bigMovieLense contains the movie ratings from 6040 users, and Groceries contains the 169 transactions in a grocery store.

Testing several algorithms on these datasets will allow to identify which algorithm is the most adapted to the business cases, as well as finding which parameters provide the best results.

In order to achieve the desired level of analysis and also to have an efficient execution time, we subset the bigMovieLense by taking 1/3 of the dataset.

## [1] "Groceries Dataset:"
## 1 x 169 rating matrix of class 'binaryRatingMatrix' with 4 ratings.
## [1] "bigMovieLense Dataset:"
## 1 x 2000 rating matrix of class 'realRatingMatrix' with 40 ratings.


Data Preparation

The bigMovieLense dataset needs to be binarized in order to explore different algorithms. The Groceries dataset is already in the right format and can be analyzed without preleminary preparation.

Pipeline

The datasets being ready, a procedure can be defined to proceed them in a consistent way, evaluate each recommendation algorithm, and decide which one is the most adapted to the business case.

The set of algorithms to be tested is:

  • Popular
  • ALS
  • AR
  • IBCF
  • UBCF


Each algorithm family requires a different set of parameters, which will be set and tuned by multiple functions to find the best combination. Some of these parameters are:

  • methods including Cosine, Pearson and Jaccard,
  • k parameter referring to the number of neighbours to be considered while calculating the similarity values,
  • nn parameter referring to the neighbourhood size used by the algorithm,
  • support parameter referring to the number of rules coming out of the association rules algorithm,
  • confidence parameter referring to the number of rules resulting from the association rules algorithm.


To identify the best set of parameters for each algorithm family, their ROC Curves will be plotted to compare the performance of the models.

Then, to compare the algorithm families, their best algorithms’ ROC Curves will be plotted on a common figure.

In order to support the choice of the final algorithm, two (2) additional tools will help drawing a conclusion:

  • An evaluation summary presenting key-metrics, like True Positive (TP), True Negative (TN), Precision, Recall. The Accuracy is also included by calculation.
  • A customer-focused analysis, which aims understanding the benefits of the models from a business point of view.


Groceries Analysis

Note: the main scripts store the datasets resulting from the algorithms in the folder RDS_GROCERIES. They are loded from there to avoid running them to generate this report.

The following charts show the ROC curves for each algorithm, plotting them for each value of the parameters that have been tested. It allows to select the best parameter value for each algorithm, considering that the highest curve is the best one.

For this dataset, Popular is performing really well. We assume that it is because, in this dataset, most of the consumers buy popular basic products, regardless of brands, tastes… such as rice, bread, milk, fruits…

For the AR, the rules above confidence 0.4 seem to fit to most of our consumers. We can see this in the summary in the next section, specifically looking at the Accuracy, which we calculated manually.

Regarding Item Based Collaborative Filtering (IBCF), the Cosine method provides better results, even though they are close to the Jaccard method results. Also, bigger is the k parameter, better the result is.

For the User Based Collaborative Filtering (UBCF), the three (3) methods look really close, regardless of the parameter value. Also, the larger the parameter nn is, the better the results of the model, but we reach a ceiling pretty fast.

Selecting the best parameter for each algorithm, it is possible to compare the algorithms on the same chart.

Looking at the Accuracy and the Precision, the AR model provides better predictions than other algorithms. It makes sense regarding our case, as for grocery products, we should check Association Rules to understand how consumers combine their purchase habits. It is one of the best way to get insights on consumers baskets, especially for recurrent products and purchases.

bigMovieLense Analysis

Note: the main scripts store the datasets resulting from the algorithms in the folder RDS_BML_SUBSET. They are loded from there to avoid running them to generate this report.

The following charts show the ROC curves for each algorithm, plotting them for each value of the parameters that have been tested. It allows to select the best parameter value for each algorithm, considering that the highest curve is the best one.

For this dataset, ALS is performing far better than Popular. In the case of movies, where tastes can evolve in time really fast, Popularity is useful only for the first steps of the users on the platform. In the long-run, it will decrease in performance.

For the AR, the confidence 0.7 helps to narrow down the options shown to the users, in order to be as personalised as possible.

Regarding Item Based Collaborative Filtering (IBCF), the Cosine method provides better results, even though they are close to the Jaccard method results. Also, bigger is the k parameter, better the result is.

For the User Based Collaborative Filtering (UBCF), the three (3) methods look really close, regardless of the parameter value. Also, the larger the parameter nn is, the better the results of the model.

Selecting the best parameter for each algorithm, it is possible to compare the algorithms on the same chart.

Looking at the Accuracy and the Precision, the UBCF model provides better predictions than other algorithms, even though every algorithm are really close in performance. Based on that, our deciding factor will be heavily weighted towards the business value. In that case, UBCF allows to provide predictions highly customised to the user preferences in reference to similar users. For further work, a combination of UBCF and IBCF should provide a more holistic approach towards our customers and a more complete scope for our recommendation engine.

Results Analysis

The two (2) datasets don’t response the same way to the different algorithms. It is mainly due to their intrinsec characterisics. The Groceries dataset relates to daily products, for which tastes might not be as disparate than for movies. This repetitive and consistent behaviour explains why the AR model is more efficient with the Groceries dataset compared to the bigMovieLense.

In the opposite, the UBCFmodel combined with IBCF (hybrid model) provides better results with the bigMovieLense, as the taste of customers can vary a lot and we need to adjust faster to the user taste changes both based on individual history but also on what similar users have also done.
